Pursuant to the requirements of the December 5, 2008 amendments to Title 40 of the Code of Federal Regulations Part 112 (40 CFR 112), as well as the Code of Maryland Regulations (COMAR) 26.10.01 governing oil pollution and tank management rules, the Plant has developed and implemented a SPCC Plan.   The SPCC Plan was prepared to address federal and state requirements for response to and prevention of spills.  Applicable regulations regarding spill prevention, reporting, and response are:

?    40 CFR 112 - Environmental Protection Agency Regulations on Oil Pollution Prevention;

?    40 CFR 110 - Discharge of Oil;

?    40 CFR 117 and 40 CFR 302.4 - Determination of Reportable Quantities for Hazardous Substances;

?    40 CFR 302 - Designation, Reportable Quantities and Notification;

?    40 CFR 300 - National Oil and Hazardous Substances Pollution Contingency Plan; 

?    40 CFR 355 - Emergency Planning and Notification; and 

?    COMAR 26.10.01.12 - Requirements for Above-Ground Oil Storage Facilities



The SPCC Plan is maintained by the Environmental Engineer.  Updates to the SPCC Plan will occur whenever there are changes to the processes taking place at the Plant which could affect storage of petroleum products.  



?    General Accidental Release Prevention Program And Chemical-Specific Prevention Steps Emergency Response Program



An emergency response program was developed for the purpose of protecting the Plant employee's health and to protect the environment.   The Plant emergency response program includes the following elements: 



?    The Plant has developed and implemented an Emergency Response Procedure (Procedure) which meets the emergency r

esponse program requirements specified in ?68.90 and ?68.95.  The Procedure is presented in Appendix B.  The purpose of this Procedure is to protect the public health and the environment and specifically addresses the following elements: 



-    Procedures for informing the public and local emergency response agencies about accidental releases; 



-    Documentation of proper first-aid and emergency medical treatment necessary to treat accidental human exposures per MSHA guidelines;  



-    Procedures and measures for emergency response after an accidental release of a regulated substance; 



-    Training for all employees in relevant procedures; and 



-    Procedures to review and update, as appropriate, the emergency response plan to reflect changes at the Plant and that it ensures that employees are informed of changes. 



As stipulated in 40 CFR 68.95(b), the Procedure complies with other Federal contingency plan regulations or is consistent with the approach in the National Response Team's Integrated Contingency Plan Guidance.   



For compliance with 40 CFR 68.95(c), the applicable elements of the Procedure are coordinated with the local community.  Upon request of the local emergency planning committee or emergency response officials, the Plant will promptly provide to the local emergency response officials information necessary for developing and implementing a community emergency response plan.



